Challange Description

The headmaster of a boarding school has installed a sundial with compass winds. To explain the 360° of a compass to his pupils he thinks up an Easter hunt starting from the sundial.
As the pupils need some exercise each egg should be at least 160m from all others.
He:

- Hides an egg always on the full degree (e.g. 0° or 37°)
- Hides exactly one egg on each degree, in total 360 eggs.
- Observes the distance rule with at least 160m (>= 160m)
- Moves away from the sundial only when necessary and always as less as possible
- Moves always clockwise
- Hides the next egg as close as possible to the last
- Hides the first egg directly north on 0° 160m from the sundial

Your task is to determine the degree and the distance of each egg.
When given the number 1 for the first egg – the degree shall be 0 and distance 160.

When given the number 13 for the 13th egg – the degree shall be 299 and distance not smaller than 329,2661.
And for any other given number between 1 and 360 for the hidden egg - you can return the correct degree and distance.

